Phase 1 — DESIGN

Objective: Define the agent's purpose, scope, and operational boundaries before a single line of code is written.

Core Question: "What should this workflow become when we remove its human friction?"

Phase 1 Activities and Deliverables

Activity Description Deliverable
Define Workflow Map the end-to-end process the agent will execute. Identify decision points, data dependencies, and current human touchpoints. Workflow Diagram with Decision Points (BPMN or similar notation)
Define Agent Roles Using the Agent Types Taxonomy (Part Three), identify which specialized agents are required. Will this be a single Cognitive Agent or a team of Action and Control Agents? Role Specification Document listing each agent type and its responsibility
Define Tools Inventory all external systems, APIs, and databases the agent must interact with to complete the workflow. Tool Registry Entries (Preliminary list with authentication requirements)
Define Memory Determine what context must persist across sessions. Does the agent need to remember user preferences from three days ago? Does it need access to a knowledge graph of product relationships? Memory Schema Document (Short-term, long-term vector, and graph requirements)
Define Success Metrics Establish the Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) that will be used in Phase 3 (Evaluate). This is the contract between the business owner and the technical team. Measurement Plan (Specific, Measurable targets for Success Rate, Latency, Cost)

Phase 1 Output

Deliverable Name: Agent Charter
The Agent Charter is the single source of truth for the agent's existence. It is signed by the Business Owner, the Technical Lead, and the Governance Lead.

Phase 1 Gate

Gate Name: Charter Approval
Requirement: Charter must be approved by Business Owner and Governance Lead.
Failure Protocol: Do not proceed to Build. Return to workflow mapping if alignment is not achieved.

