PART THREE: AGENT TYPES TAXONOMY (STANDARDIZED)

Status: Canonical Classification System
Scope: Workforce Composition, Role Definition, and Agent Architecture

---

🔹 Preamble to the Taxonomy

The 10 Laws (Part One) established that specialization trumps general intelligence. The Agent Lifecycle (Part Two) defined the process for building and deploying a single agent. Part Three addresses the critical question that arises when you scale beyond one agent: "What kinds of agents should we build, and how do they work together?"

A standardized taxonomy is essential for three reasons:

1. Communication: It provides a shared vocabulary between business stakeholders, workflow architects, and engineers. When someone says "We need a Cognitive Agent," everyone understands the scope.
2. Reusability: Standardized agent types can be templated, versioned, and deployed across multiple workflows without reinventing the wheel.
3. Governance: Different agent classes have different risk profiles. A Governance Agent requires stricter access controls than a Research Agent.

This taxonomy is the organizational chart for your digital workforce.

---

🔹 The 4 Classes of Agents (Canonical Hierarchy)

All agents fall into one of four primary classes, defined by their core function within the enterprise. This is not a technical limitation but a design pattern for composable systems.

