🔹 Class 1: COGNITIVE AGENTS (THINK)

Core Function: Perception, analysis, and synthesis of information. Cognitive Agents do not change the state of external systems; they produce insights, plans, and recommendations.

Risk Profile: Low to Medium. Errors in this class primarily result in bad advice, not direct operational damage. However, in high-stakes domains (healthcare, finance), a faulty recommendation can cascade into Action Agent errors.

Lifecycle Phase Emphasis: Phase 1 (Design) and Phase 3 (Evaluate Hallucination Rate).

Cognitive Agent Subtypes

Agent Type Primary Function Key Capabilities Example Use Case Input/Output Pattern
Research Agent Synthesize information from multiple sources and validate citations. Web search, internal document retrieval (RAG), source credibility scoring, citation generation. Competitive intelligence briefing; Market trend analysis; Due diligence research. Input: Query → Output: Structured report with citations.
Reasoning Agent Apply logical deduction to complex, multi-variable problems. Chain-of-Thought (CoT), Tree-of-Thoughts (ToT), Graph-of-Thoughts (GoT), constraint satisfaction. Root cause analysis of IT incident; Legal contract clause analysis; Medical differential diagnosis support. Input: Problem statement + data → Output: Logical conclusion with evidence chain.
Planning Agent Decompose high-level goals into executable, ordered tasks with dependencies. Task decomposition, dependency mapping, resource estimation, critical path identification. Project plan generation; Sprint planning; Supply chain route optimization. Input: Goal → Output: Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) of tasks.

Integration with Agentic Enterprise Stack:
Cognitive Agents reside primarily in Layer 3 (Agent Layer) but heavily depend on Layer 6 (Data Layer) for accurate knowledge retrieval.

---

🔹 Class 2: ACTION AGENTS (DO)

Core Function: Execution of tasks that change the state of external systems or data. Action Agents are the "hands" of the agentic workforce.

Risk Profile: Medium to High. Errors in this class result in direct operational consequences—incorrect database writes, erroneous API calls, or broken business processes. Pre-execution validation is mandatory.

Lifecycle Phase Emphasis: Phase 2 (Build Tool Connectors) and Phase 4 (Shadow Mode Deployment).

Action Agent Subtypes

Agent Type Primary Function Key Capabilities Example Use Case Input/Output Pattern
Execution Agent Perform discrete, atomic tasks via tools or APIs. API invocation, database CRUD operations, file system manipulation, email sending. Updating a CRM record; Creating a Jira ticket; Sending a status notification. Input: Structured command → Output: Execution confirmation or error.
Automation Agent Run end-to-end, multi-step workflows that may involve multiple systems. Workflow engine integration (e.g., Temporal, Camunda), state management, retry logic with exponential backoff. Order-to-cash processing; Employee onboarding sequence; Invoice approval workflow. Input: Workflow trigger event → Output: Workflow completion status.
Integration Agent Connect and translate between legacy systems that lack modern APIs. Screen scraping (ethical and governed), legacy protocol translation, data format transformation (EDI to JSON). Integrating a mainframe inventory system with a modern cloud ERP; Data synchronization between acquired company systems. Input: Data from System A → Output: Data in format for System B.

Critical Design Pattern for Action Agents:
Pre-Execution Validation Hook: Before any state-changing operation (SQL UPDATE, API POST), the Action Agent must pass the proposed change through a Validation Agent (a specialized Cognitive or Governance agent) that confirms the operation is within policy and expected bounds.

---

🔹 Class 3: CONTROL AGENTS (COORDINATE)

Core Function: Management of the multi-agent system itself. Control Agents are the "nervous system" that ensures the swarm behaves as a coherent unit rather than a chaotic mob.

Risk Profile: High. Failure of a Control Agent results in ASI08: Cascading Failures across the entire agent workforce.

Lifecycle Phase Emphasis: Phase 2 (Orchestration Graph) and Phase 5 (Monitoring).

Control Agent Subtypes

Agent Type Primary Function Key Capabilities Example Use Case Input/Output Pattern
Orchestration Agent Manage the execution of a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) across multiple specialized agents. State machine management, dependency resolution, parallel task fan-out/fan-in, error handling and rollback. Coordinating a Research Agent → Planning Agent → Execution Agent workflow for a quarterly business review. Input: DAG definition → Output: Orchestrated execution trace.
Supervisor Agent Oversee the performance of a team of agents, ensuring quality and handling escalations. Quality assurance checks, confidence threshold monitoring, escalation routing to human supervisors (Law 10). Reviewing outputs of multiple Execution Agents before final approval; Detecting "Arrogant" agent behavior. Input: Agent outputs → Output: Approval/Rejection/Escalation signal.
Routing Agent Direct incoming tasks to the most appropriate specialized agent or model based on content and cost constraints. Intent classification, semantic similarity matching, cost-aware model selection (e.g., route simple queries to Haiku, complex to Opus). Intelligent load balancing in a customer support swarm; Optimizing inference costs across multiple model providers. Input: User query → Output: Designated target agent/model.

Canonical Frameworks for Control Agents:

· LangGraph: Preferred for production Orchestration Agents due to its explicit state management and durable execution capabilities.
· CrewAI: Preferred for rapid prototyping of Supervisor Agents where the team structure is role-based.
· AutoGen: Preferred for complex Routing Agents and negotiation patterns between agents.

---

🔹 Class 4: GOVERNANCE AGENTS (PROTECT)

Core Function: Continuous enforcement of security, compliance, and policy guardrails across the entire agentic ecosystem.

Risk Profile: Critical. Failure of a Governance Agent constitutes an EU AI Act Article 14 violation and exposes the enterprise to legal, financial, and reputational ruin.

Lifecycle Phase Emphasis: Phase 7 (Govern). This class runs continuously alongside all other phases.

Governance Agent Subtypes

Agent Type Primary Function Key Capabilities Example Use Case Input/Output Pattern
Audit Agent Track and log all agent actions, inputs, and outputs in an immutable ledger. Event sourcing, cryptographic hashing of action chains, tamper-evident log generation. Generating compliance reports for SOX, GDPR, or EU AI Act audits; Forensic analysis of a security incident. Input: Agent telemetry stream → Output: Immutable audit trail.
Compliance Agent Enforce policies and regulatory rules in real-time. Policy-as-code evaluation, PII redaction, prompt injection detection (ASI01), least-privilege access verification. Blocking an Action Agent from sending customer PII to an external LLM; Flagging a high-risk financial transaction for human review. Input: Proposed action + context → Output: Allow/Block/Flag signal.
Monitoring Agent Detect drift, anomalies, and potential rogue behavior across the agent fleet. Behavioral baseline establishment, anomaly detection (statistical and ML-based), alert generation (Phase 5 integration). Detecting an Execution Agent that suddenly starts writing to a database table it never used before (ASI10 Rogue Agent indicator). Input: Metrics stream → Output: Anomaly alert.

Integration with OWASP ASI Top 10:
Governance Agents are the primary technical mitigation for:

· ASI01: Agent Goal Hijack (Compliance Agent detects prompt injection)
· ASI02: Tool Misuse (Compliance Agent enforces least-privilege)
· ASI06: Memory Poisoning (Monitoring Agent detects embedding drift)
· ASI10: Rogue Agents (Monitoring Agent detects behavioral anomalies)

