🔹 Layer 3: AGENT LAYER

Position: Core Execution
Ownership: AI Engineers, Prompt Engineers
Lifecycle Phase Alignment: Phase 2 (Build), Phase 3 (Evaluate)

Purpose

This is the "brain" of the system. It defines the cognitive architecture, reasoning patterns, and memory structures of individual agents. This layer implements the Agent Types Taxonomy (Part Three).

Canonical Components

Component Description Technology/Pattern
Planner Module The component responsible for decomposing a goal into a plan (ReAct, Plan-and-Execute). LangGraph create_react_agent or custom DAG generator.
Executor Module The component that invokes tools based on the plan. Tool-calling function definitions.
Critic/Evaluator Module A self-reflection loop that validates agent output against a rubric. Separate LLM call for validation.
Short-Term Memory In-context window management and conversation history. Sliding window summarization.
Long-Term Memory Semantic search over past interactions and enterprise knowledge. Vector Database integration (Pinecone, Weaviate).
Role Specialization System prompts and few-shot examples tailored to a specific Agent Type (e.g., Reasoning Agent vs. Execution Agent). Version-controlled Prompt Library.
TTL (Time-To-Live) Policies Rules for how long specific memory items are retained for privacy and relevance. Data retention policy enforcement.

Canonical Reasoning Patterns (2026 Standard)

Pattern Implementation Use Case
ReAct Agent iterates: Thought → Action → Observation → Thought General-purpose task execution.
Tree-of-Thoughts (ToT) Agent explores multiple reasoning branches concurrently. Complex planning and problem-solving.
Graph-of-Thoughts (GoT) Agent models reasoning as a graph, allowing cycles and recombination of ideas. Research synthesis and creative ideation.

2026 Imperative

All agents must expose a Calibration Endpoint that returns the agent's confidence score alongside its output. This is required for the Trust Dashboard (Skeptic's Addendum) and for Phase 3 Evaluation.

