🔹 Layer 4: ORCHESTRATION LAYER

Position: Central Nervous System
Ownership: Platform Engineers, AI Architects
Lifecycle Phase Alignment: Phase 2 (Build - Orchestration Graph), Phase 5 (Monitor)

Purpose

This layer operationalizes Law 7: Orchestration Is the OS. It manages the execution of multi-agent workflows, handling state, routing, and error recovery. This is the operating system of the agentic enterprise.

Canonical Components

Component Description Implementation
Task Decomposition Engine Translates a high-level goal into a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) of sub-tasks. LangGraph StateGraph with conditional edges.
State Machine Maintains the current state of every active workflow instance. Durable execution storage (PostgreSQL, Redis).
Event Router Directs messages and outputs between agents based on content and workflow rules. Pub/Sub system (Kafka, NATS).
Scheduler Manages concurrency, rate limits, and time-based triggers. Temporal.io, Celery, or cloud-native schedulers.
Error Boundary & Fallback Chains Defines what happens when an agent fails (retry, fallback to simpler model, escalate to human). Circuit breaker pattern implementation.

Framework Selection Matrix (Canonical)

Framework Primary Use Case Strengths Weaknesses
LangGraph Production-grade, stateful multi-agent workflows. Explicit state management, durable execution, great observability. Steeper learning curve; more code required.
CrewAI Rapid prototyping of role-based agent teams. Intuitive developer experience, fast iteration. Less fine-grained control over state; can be brittle at scale.
AutoGen Complex agent conversations and negotiation patterns; Azure environments. Excellent for multi-turn dialogues; native Azure integration. Event-driven model can be difficult to debug.

2026 Imperative

Implement Circuit Breakers between all agent-to-agent and agent-to-tool calls to prevent ASI08: Cascading Failures. A single unresponsive API must not deadlock the entire orchestration layer.

