🔹 Layer 5: TOOL LAYER

Position: Interface to External Systems
Ownership: API Platform Team, Integration Architects
Lifecycle Phase Alignment: Phase 2 (Build - Tool Connectors)

Purpose

This layer operationalizes Law 4: Tools Define Power. It provides agents with a secure, standardized, and observable interface to the outside world.

Canonical Components

Component Description Standard
MCP Connectors The Model Context Protocol standard for connecting AI agents to tools. This is the canonical standard for 2026. MCP Specification (Anthropic)
Custom API Wrappers For legacy systems that do not yet support MCP. REST/GraphQL with OpenAPI schema validation.
RPA (Robotic Process Automation) Bridges For systems with no API (e.g., green-screen mainframes). Ethical and governed screen scraping.
Tool Registry A centralized catalog of all available tools, including their schemas, authentication requirements, and rate limits. Backstage or custom registry.
Schema Validation Layer Validates that the agent's intended tool call matches the required input schema before execution. Pydantic, Zod, or JSON Schema.
Rate-Limit & Auth Policies Enforces per-agent, per-tool usage limits and manages OAuth 2.1 token refresh. API Gateway (Kong, Apigee).

The MCP Imperative (2026)

By early 2026, the Model Context Protocol has achieved critical mass:

· 20,000+ MCP servers.
· 97 million monthly SDK downloads.
· 28% Fortune 500 adoption (doubling year-over-year).

Strategic Mandate: All new internal APIs and services must expose an MCP-compatible endpoint. The Tool Registry should prioritize MCP servers.

Pre-Execution Validation Hook (Critical Pattern)

Before an Action Agent executes any state-changing operation (e.g., SQL DELETE, API POST), the Tool Layer must invoke a Validation Hook that checks the proposed action against the Governance Layer's policies. This prevents ASI02: Tool Misuse and Exploitation.

